Anyway---<br>
<br>
The existance of a &quot;knee&quot; in the dmg vs. AC &quot;curve&quot; is EASILY demonstratable and has been posted numerous times.  It's not really subject to debate, but if you REALLY wish to test it, it's trivial to do.  The observed result is that mobs that severely outclass the pc will hit for max damage most of the time; at some point in increasing AC/level/etc, the same mob starts hitting for intermediate damage, and the mode damage (most common hit) drops from the max value.  As the difference increases even more, the mode damage a mob hits for drops to the min damage it can hit for.  It is NOT a smooth transition at all, and the &quot;critical&quot; range of AC can be as little as 20-30pts.  About a zillion ways to test this, use your imagination, but I'm really surprised you hadn't noticed it??  You obviously have to look at the damage distribution to see it clearly, but it's super obvious when you plot it out.  Heck, you can see it when fighting mobs yourself- you hit ones with higher AC for minimum damage (mode 1 pt) offhand, unless you get piles of STR/ATK buffs and/or someone debuffs the mobs AC.  Other (blue) mobs you hit for intermediate values, and greenies you hit typically for full.  Same deal, different values in the variables tho I'd imagine.<br>
<br>
Also, extrapolation of a indeterministic nonlinear function (damage/attack in EQ) is WAY different from extrapolation of human behavior (lazy verant programmers re-using functions from other parts of the codebase).  There's a demonstrable &quot;knee&quot; in dmg/AC for lower levels, why change it at higher ones?  Heck, on the flip side, there's a verant &quot;confirmed&quot; softcap (900?) in the old world- it's no stretch to suggest there isn't one in velious/luclin too.    Make more sense now? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      <br>
<br>
Gonna try a ascii plot (dmg = mode dmg/hit)<br>
<br>
|.......................<br>
d.......................<br>
m++++...............&lt;max hit<br>
g........++...........<br>
|...........++.........<br>
|...............+++++&lt;min hit<br>
+-----AC---------<br>
__________^ <br>
Critical AC value, VERY dependent on other variables tho, but ALL else being equal is always at the same place.<br>
<br>
Note that *IF* there was a softcap, and it was low enough, you'd never get to the point where you'd get minimum hits as the mode; there's basically no way to tell the difference between the two then!<br>
<br>
Think of it this way- to a level 50 player in old world gear, a juggy ATK is effectively WAY superior to what AC he can reach, and he gets clocked for full dmg almost every hit.  Sure looks like a softcap doesn't it!?  Can't see that there isn't until you get past the combination of AC/Level/etc. necessary to overwhelm the mob's ATK to observe that there isn't one there.  We can do that in the old world (~900) and kunark (~1100), but I haven't see or experienced anything in luclin that suggests where, if at all, there is one.  There MIGHT be, but there's no evidence that there is, or where it's at.<br>
<br>
Moral: if the fully debuffed mob hits you for max damage &quot;all the time&quot; (i.e. mode hit) when you are fully buffed and in AC gear, then HP is obviously the way to go.  If newer/more-uber AC gear or better/bigger mob debuffs become available, it's worth checking AC.  There simply isn't any other way to tell the difference right now, barring a spoiler from verant.<br>
<br>
I think.<br>
